1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 c4 {
If Black wants to play this move it should be done as soon as possible as
otherwise White can prevent this resource.} ({for example} 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O
9. dxc5) 8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ye5c6] As after c5-c4 it is harder to
create pressure against the d5-pawn, White changes the structure in order to
have new targets in Black's camp.} O-O 10. b3 $5 {I like the move order chosen
by White in this game.} (10. Bg5 {would transpose to the main lines}) 10...
cxb3 (10... Qa5 11. Bb2 Bb4 12. Rc1 cxb3 13. axb3 Be6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Na4 $14
{[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc1c6] ;Khenkin,I (2638)-Vilar Lopez,M (2145) Andorra op 21st
2003 (1) 1-0 also gave a typical edge for White in}) 11. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 12. axb3
{[%csl Ya7,Yc6] Now White can play against the c6 and a7 pawns.} a5 13. Ba3 $1
{[%csl Gc5] A very important positional operation for White. After this
exchange he get rid of Black's good bishop and can use the important c5-square
which gives him a small but pleasant advantage.} Re8 14. Qc2 Ba6 15. Rfc1 ({
even simpler was} 15. Bxe7 $1 {preventing the idea that Black tried in the game
} Rxe7 (15... Qxe7 $2 16. Rxa5 Bd3 {[%cal Ya8a5]} 17. Qa2 $1 Rxa5 18. Qxa5 $16
Bxe2 $2 19. Re1 {[%csl Re2]}) 16. Rfc1 {[%cal Ye2e3,Gc3a4,Ga4c5] White can
continue with e3 and Na4-c5, with easier play and a pleasant advantage. Black
faces a difficult choice: the passive defense will be long and unpleasant, but
active measures don't work either, for example} Rc8 17. e3 c5 18. Bh3 $1 Rc6 (
18... Rcc7 19. Qd2 {[%cal Ya1a5]} cxd4 20. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rd5]}) 19. Na4
$1 c4 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. Bf1 $1 cxb3 22. Qxb3 $16 {[%csl Ga5,Gd5] and Black only
succeeded to make things easier for White. The knight has achieved its
excellent outpost on c5 and the pawns on d5 and a5 remain weak. It is likely
that the a5-pawn will be lost in some moves, leaving Black suffering.}) 15...
Bb4 $1 {Getting rid of the knight is the best chance for Black.} 16. e3 (16.
Bxb4 axb4 17. Na4 Rxe2 18. Qxc6 Re6 19. Qc5 Rb8 {seems ok for Black}) 16...
Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Bb5 {[%csl Yc6] The bad bishop protects a good pawn!} 18. Bc5 a4
$1 {Black managed to deal with his queenside problems.} (18... Ne4 {was an
interesting option too} 19. Qc2 Ra6 {[%cal Yd8d7,Ye8a8,Ya5a4] Black can
mobilize his forces on the queenside and prepare to push a5-a4 under better
circumstances.}) 19. bxa4 Rxa4 20. Rxa4 Bxa4 {With only one weakness remaining,
and well protected by the bishop, Black is probably able to equalize.} 21. Ra1
(21. Bf1 Ne4 22. Qb4 Qf6 $1 23. f4 (23. Qxa4 $2 Qxf2+ 24. Kh1 Qf3+ 25. Bg2 Nf2+
26. Kg1 Qxe3 $19 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gf2h3]}) 23... Nxc5 24. Rxc5 Qe7 $1 25. Qxa4
(25. Qc3 Rb8 $132) 25... Qxe3+ 26. Kg2 Qe4+ $11) 21... Bb5 22. Qc2 g6 $6 {
A strange move which creates unnecessary weaknesses on the dark squares on the
kingside.} (22... Ne4 {would be good, initiating a good defensive maneuver} 23.
Bb4 h6 24. f3 Ng5 $1 {[%cal Yg5e6] covering c5}) 23. Ra7 Kg7 24. Qa2 $1 h5 25.
Qa3 $1 {[%cal Ga3a8,Ga3f8] White makes excellent use of the open lines. In
addition to the a-file, he can also use the weakened dark-squares.} Qc8 26. Bd6
{[%cal Yd6e5]} Qf5 27. Qb2 $1 {Attentive.} (27. Be5 $4 Qb1+ {and White is mated
}) 27... h4 $2 {Maybe Black misevalueted this move and the arising position.} (
27... g5 $1 28. Be5 Kg6 $1 {was still totally playable}) 28. gxh4 Qg4 {[%cal
Gg4d1]} 29. Qa1 $1 Qxh4 30. Be5 $16 {The main problem for Black is that he is
almost paralyzed now.} Bd3 $6 {[%cal Yd3e4]} (30... Qg5 31. Qd1 {[%cal Yd1f3]}
Qf5 32. h3 $1 (32. Qf3 $2 Qb1+) 32... g5 33. Qf3 $1 Qxf3 34. Bxf3 Kg6 35. Bd1
$1 {[%cal Gd1c2] and Black is still under heavy pressure}) 31. Rc7 $1 Kg8 (
31... Bb5 32. Qa7 Rf8 33. h3 $1 Kg8 34. Qb7 $18 {[%cal Yc7c8]}) 32. Bg3 Qg5 33.
Rxc6 $16 {The rest is simple technique.} Ne4 34. Qa4 Rd8 35. Qa5 Nxg3 36. hxg3
Rb8 37. Rb6 Rc8 38. Qxd5 Rc1+ 39. Kh2 Qh6+ 40. Bh3 Bf5 41. Rb8+ (41. Qxf5 $1)
41... Bc8 42. Qd8+ 1-0

