1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. d4 Be7 8. Nc3
O-O 9. dxc5 d4 $5 10. Na4 Bf5 11. a3 $5 {[%cal Yb2b4,Yc1b2] This is safe and
reliable, White intends to protect the pawn first and only then to solve the
development problem.} (11. b4 d3 $1 {creates some complications, exactly what
Black is looking for}) (11. e3 $2 {is not only bad but it is actually losing:}
dxe3 12. Qxd8 (12. Bxe3 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 Bc2 $19) 12... exf2+ 13. Rxf2 Raxd8 $17)
11... Be4 {Aiming for quick centralization.} ({the direct} 11... b5 12. cxb6
axb6 {[%cal Yb6b5]} 13. b4 $1 $146 {gives better chances for White}) (11... d3
$2 {is also a direct approach, but after} 12. Re1 $1 {White is better again}
dxe2 13. Qxe2 Qa5 14. Qc4 Be6 (14... Rad8 15. Bd2 $1 Rxd2 $2 16. Nxd2 Qxd2 17.
Bxc6 $18 {[%csl Re7]}) 15. Rxe6 $1 {now the initiative passes to White's hands}
fxe6 16. Bd2 Qd8 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 {Demir,G (2239)-Adams,N (2205) Budapest FS12 IM
2008 (5) 1/2} 18. Be3 $16 {White is a pawn up on both sides, he has good
pieces and the opponent's king is weak, which is more than enough compensation
for the exchange}) (11... Ne4 {[%csl Gc5] is another possible set-up for Black,
winning time by attacking c5} 12. b4 {and now} Bf6 {[%csl Yf5,Yf6][%cal Ge4c3]
Black pieces are looking very active, but White is in time to keep the control}
(12... Nc3 $146 {actually is an improved version only for White} 13. Nxc3 dxc3
14. Qb3 Bf6 15. Be3 {The c3-pawn is simply harmless for White, even if the
game follows the line} a6 16. Rac1 Re8 17. Rxc3 $1 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 {[%csl Ga3,
Gb4,Gc5,Yg2] again, White has pawns up on both sides and the queenside
majority supported by the Bg2 is very strong, for example} Be4 19. Qa1 $1 {
[%cal Yf1d1]} Qe7 20. Bf4 Rad8 21. Bd6 Qf6 22. Qxf6 gxf6 23. Rc1 $14) 13. Bb2 {
[%cal Yb4b5]} Nc3 $8 14. Bxc3 dxc3 15. Qb3 {Black is forced to advance the pawn
} c2 16. Rac1 Re8 {White can consider exchange sacrifice ideas, but there's
even an easier and very forcing path to the advantage} 17. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Ye2e4]
} a5 (17... Bxc3 $2 18. Qxc3 Rxe2 19. b5 $18 {[%cal Gf3d4]}) 18. b5 a4 (18...
Nd4 19. Nxd4 Qxd4 20. e4 $1 $16) 19. Qd5 $1 {[%cal Yd5f5] very precise} Ne7 20.
Qxd8 Rexd8 21. e4 $1 {White eliminates the pawn and keeps the material
advantage} Rac8 22. exf5 Bxc3 23. Rxc2 Rxc5 24. Rfc1 Rdc8 25. Ne1 $1 $16 {
L'Ami,E (2627) -Berelowitsch,A (2565) NED-chT 1213 2012 (7.1) 1-0}) 12. b4 Qd5
{[%csl Yd5,Ye4][%cal Gf6d5,Gf6e4] Black has centralized the pieces, but now
the knight has no access points to reach c3, so White can simply continue
developing the pieces onto good squares.} 13. Bf4 $1 h6 $2 {Too slow.} ({
The direct} 13... g5 $5 {looks like Black's best attempt, but is still bad} 14.
Bd2 $1 Nd7 15. Nb2 Nce5 16. Nd3 $1 Nc4 {Benjamin,J (2255)-Todorovic,G (2410)
London Peace 1987 1/2} (16... Nxd3 17. exd3 Bxd3 18. Nxg5 $18) 17. Qb3 $1 {
and White manages to develop the remaining pieces with an excellent position}
Rfd8 (17... g4 $2 18. Nf4 $1 Nxd2 19. Nxd2 $18) 18. Rfd1 Bf6 19. Rac1 $16) (
13... Rfe8 14. Rc1 {[%cal Ya4b2,Yb2c4]}) 14. Rc1 g5 15. Bd6 $1 $16 {Having the
rook on c1 makes all the difference, now White is much better.} b5 (15... Bxd6
16. cxd6 Qxd6 (16... b6 17. Rxc6 $1 Qxc6 18. Qxd4 $16 {[%cal Yd4f6,Gf3e5]}) 17.
Nc5 {[%cal Yc5b7,Yc5e4] and White is going to have a material advantage again.}
) 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Nb2 Nc6 (17... Qa2 18. Qxd4 $18) 18. Nd3 Rfe8 19. Qd2 {
Already from this point we can call White's position winning: He is up a
healthy passed pawn and has nice squares for the pieces. Black can put some
resistance, as he did, but objectively speaking, White should convert his
advantage.} Rad8 20. h4 $1 Nh7 (20... g4 21. Nfe1 {[%cal Yd3f4,Ye1d3]}) 21. a4
$1 {White's use of both rook pawns to improve the position is very instructive.
} a6 22. axb5 axb5 23. Ra1 Re6 24. Ra6 Qf5 25. Rb6 $18 Bd5 26. Ra1 Rde8 27. Re1
Qg6 28. hxg5 hxg5 29. Rxb5 Bxf3 30. Bxf3 g4 31. Nf4 Qh6 32. Bxc6 Rxc6 33. Kg2
Ng5 34. Rh1 Qg7 35. Rb6 Rxb6 36. cxb6 Qf6 37. b7 Ne4 38. Qc2 1-0

