1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 c5 {With the other knight still on b1, this move
order gives more options for White.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O
Be7 8. Nc3 ({Another interesting set-up would be} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 {
[%csl Gd4][%cal Yd2b3] establishing a quick blockade on d4.}) 8... O-O 9. dxc5
$1 Bxc5 10. Na4 Be7 11. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Yd4] White's plan is clear and easy to
understand. He wants to obtain as much control over the very important d4- and
c5-squares. The first one is an important blockading square. For White it
would be nice to land a knight on c5 from where it would put further pressure
on Black's position.} Bg4 12. Rc1 Re8 {Black continues to develop the pieces
actively.} 13. Nc5 $5 {White tries to force Black to give the important
dark-squared bishop.} Bxc5 (13... Qb6 $5 {is an option to avoid that exchange
for now. White would answer with} 14. Nb3 {[%cal Yb3d4,Yb3c5] keeping Nd4 and
Nc5 at his disposal.}) 14. Bxc5 {[%csl Yc5,Yg2] Although the knight was useful
on c5, the bishop pair also gives White a nice position.} Qd7 15. Re1 {[%cal
Gf3d4] The next step is to prepare Nd4.} Bh3 (15... Rac8 {looks good to
prevent Nd4, but White can still fight for an advantage} 16. Bd4 $5 Ne4 (16...
Nxd4 17. Qxd4 $1 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 (18... Rxe2 $2 19. Ne5 $18) 19. Rxc8+ Qxc8
20. h3 $1 Bxh3 21. Bxh3 Qxh3 22. Qxa7 $14 {White keeps the better position,
besides the isolani he can work with the queenside majority now}) 17. Be3 {
[%cal Yf3d4] after spending a tempo on Bd4-e3, White is finally ready for Nd4.}
h5 $5 {Pigusov,E (2455)-Lputian,S (2530) Chigorin Memorial-19 1985 1/2} 18. Qa4
Bh3 19. Bxh3 Qxh3 20. Qb3 Qd7 21. Red1 Red8 22. Kg2 $14) 16. Bh1 $1 {Keeping
this bishop also looks like a correct decision.} Ne4 17. Be3 Rad8 18. Nd4 (18.
Qa4 $5 {is not only interesting but also provocative as it tempts Black to push
} d4 $2 {when he would suddenly find himself in a lost position after} 19. Nxd4
$1 Nxd4 20. Qxd7 Rxd7 21. Bxe4 $16 {Mindlin,A (2450)-Novik,M (2482) Maccabiah
GM-B 2017 (4) 1-0 due to the back rank ideas White is a pawn up.}) 18... Ne5
19. Bf4 {White is still looking for exchanges.} Qe7 (19... Nc4 {doesn't
changes much after} 20. b3) 20. Bxe5 $1 {Now White has a practical advantage
with no risks. In general, this is what White players should look for when
fighting against an isolated pawn.} Qxe5 21. e3 Rd6 $5 {Black is looking for a
play on the kingside.} 22. Rc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2f2,Gc2b2,Ge1c1] Nice prophylaxis
by the Cuban GM. He protects the second rank and prepares to double rooks on
the c-file.} Rg6 23. Qe2 a6 24. Rec1 h5 {[%cal Yh5h4] Apparently, Black is
doing well and has a dangerous initiative coming on the kingside, but now
White made a very instructive decision:} 25. Bxe4 $1 Qxe4 (25... dxe4 $2 26.
Rc5 {[%csl Rh5]}) 26. Qf3 $1 {This leaves Black with a difficult choice.} Qe5
$6 (26... Rf6 {was possibly the best option, with an almost forced sequence}
27. Qxe4 dxe4 28. Rc7 (28. Rc5 $5) 28... b5 29. R1c6 $1 Rxc6 30. Rxc6 Rc8 $1
31. Rxc8+ Bxc8 32. Kf1 {with an endgame that usually should be unpleasant for
Black due to his many weaknesses on the dark squares, but there are chances to
hold. But going into such an endgame is a difficult decision to make during a
game.}) 27. Rc5 Rd8 28. Qf4 $1 {This is a model game on how well-timed,
correct exchanges can yield an advantage. The arising endgame is notably
easier to play as White.} Qxf4 29. exf4 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc1c8,Yf2f3,Yg1f2]
White has the open c-file under control, he can bring the king to the game
using f3-Kf2, and the Nd4 is a monster, protecting the important e2-square.
Black's position is unpleasant which often leads to further mistakes in such
endgames.} Rb6 (29... h4 $2 {doesn't prevent White's plan} 30. f3 $1 hxg3 31.
hxg3 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gg3g4] and now g4 is a serious threat} Rxg3+ $2 32. Kh2
$18 {[%csl Rg3,Rh3]}) 30. b3 g6 31. f3 Rbd6 32. b4 {Slowly but steadily, White
improves his position.} Kf8 33. a3 Bf5 34. R1c3 Ke7 35. Kf2 Kf6 36. Rc7 R8d7
37. Ke3 Rxc7 38. Rxc7 Rd7 39. Rc5 $1 {It is often good to trade one pair of
rooks, but now White should avoid it because his rook is better than Black's
one, which is passively placed.} Be6 40. a4 Ke7 41. a5 {Fixing the pawns on
the same square as the bishop is an advisable strategy, but White had an idea
that was stronger.} ({It was} 41. Nc2 $1 Kd6 42. Kd4 $1 {[%cal Gc2e3] with a
nice regrouped to press the d5-pawn. A nice concept to remember is that the
d4-square is good for the knight for the most part of the game, especially
during the middlegame. But the fewer pieces are left on the board in the
endgame, the more likely it will be that the king should be on that square.})
41... Kd6 42. Rc3 (42. f5 $5) 42... Re7 43. Kd2 {In the end White lost the
chance to improve his set-up, and Black is holding. But as a rule of thumb,
such endgames always provide practical chances for the first player, and the
defense is a difficult and tiring job.} Bd7 44. Re3 Be6 45. Rc3 Bd7 46. Rc1 Re8
47. Rc5 Rb8 48. h4 Re8 (48... b6 $5 49. axb6 Rxb6 50. Kc3 Be6 {would give
drawing chances for Black}) 49. Rc3 f6 50. Nb3 {After shuffling around for a
while, White tries something.} Rg8 $6 {As it was said, the defence requires a
lot of attention in such cases.} (50... Re7 {was a safer option} 51. Nc5 Bc6
52. Re3 Rxe3 53. Kxe3 d4+ $1 $11 {[%csl Yf3]}) 51. Nc5 Bc8 (51... Rb8 52. g4 $5
hxg4 53. Nxd7 Kxd7 54. fxg4 {[%cal Yc3h3,Yh4h5] and White has some chances in
this rook endgame}) 52. Re3 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gc3d4]} g5 $5 {Black should try
something active, or White would just play Ke3-d4 with an already clear
advantage.} (52... Rd8 53. Kc3 Kc6 54. Re2 $1 {Black is in a sort of zugzwang.}
d4+ (54... Kb5 55. Nb3 $1 {[%cal Gb3d4]} Kc6 56. Re7 $16) 55. Kc4 Bf5 56. Ne6 {
winning the pawn}) 53. fxg5 fxg5 54. hxg5 Rxg5 55. f4 Rg8 56. Re5 $5 (56. Kc3 {
[%cal Gc3d4]} Rf8 $1 {[%cal Yh5h4]}) 56... Rxg3 57. Rxh5 Rf3 58. Rh6+ Kc7 59.
Rf6 {Black's position seems still a bit unpleasant, as the Bc8 is not playing
much, due to the pressure on b7, but with correct play he should be able to
hold.} d4 60. Nd3 Bh3 61. Rf7+ Kc8 $2 {The decisive mistake.} ({It was
important for Black to play actively with} 61... Kd6 $1 62. Rxb7 Bf5 $1 {
taking advantage of his better coordinated pieces and the passed pawn} 63. Nc5
Kd5 $1 64. Nxa6 Rf2+ 65. Ke1 Ra2 66. Nc5 Ra1+ 67. Kf2 Ra2+ $132 {because of
the passed pawn on d4, the White king cannot go so far, and the result should
be a draw already}) (61... Kb8 {would be better too}) 62. Nc5 Rc3 63. Ne4 $1 {
Now Black's position becomes really difficult.} (63. Nxb7 {was also good})
63... Rc6 64. Kd3 $18 {[%csl Rd4] The pawn is lost, the king comes to the game,
basically it is over.} Bf1+ (64... Bg2 {wouldn't be better} 65. Kxd4 Bxe4 66.
Kxe4 Rc4+ 67. Ke5 Rxb4 68. f5 Rb5+ 69. Kd6 Kb8 70. f6 Rxa5 71. Rg7 Rf5 72. f7
Ka7 73. Ke6 Rf2 74. Rg5 $1 $18) 65. Kxd4 Rc4+ 66. Kd5 Rxb4 67. Nd6+ Kb8 68. f5
Bg2+ 69. Ke6 Bc6 70. Rf8+ 1-0

