1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 {The most solid variation.} ({
There's a famous game which illustrates White's attacking chances pretty well:
} 11... Nc6 12. O-O b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Rfe1 Na5 (14... Rc8 15. d5 Na5 16. Bd3
$1 {transposes to the text.}) 15. Bd3 Rc8 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. e5 $1 {[%cal
Gf3d4,Gd4f5,Ye5e6,Yf3g5] This typical pawn sacrifice gives very good attacking
prospects to White. He has ideas like Nd4-f5 or Ng5; even e5-e6 would leave
Black's king more exposed. Black tried to force exchanges with} Nc4 18. Qf4 Nb2
$2 {but then} 19. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 20. Ng5+ Kg6 21. h4 $3 {Polugaevsky,L-Tal,M
URS-ch37 Final 1969 (2) 1-0 gave White a powerful attack in} Nxd1 $2 {loses to}
22. h5+ $1 Kxh5 23. g4+ Kg6 24. Qf5+ Kh6 25. Qh7+ $1 Kxg5 26. Qh5+ Kf4 27. Qf5#
) 12. O-O b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. d5 $5 {White tries to break in the center
immediately and avoids giving Black time to develop the pieces.} (14. Rfe1 Rc8
15. Bb3 Re8 {has been the main option on a top level.}) 14... exd5 15. Bxd5 {
[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5a8,Gd5g8] White hopes to keep some pressure in the center
with this bishop, and, after an eventual exchange, to have a strong passed
pawn on the d-file.} (15. exd5 {seems harmless for Black after} Rc8 16. Bb3 Nc5
$11 {and the d-pawn is not dangerous here}) 15... Nc5 ({of course} 15... Bxd5
$2 {is bad because after} 16. exd5 {[%cal Yd5d6] Black is not able to prevent
the advance d5-d6, then the pawn becomes very annoying in Black's camp. A nice
classic example of this is the famous game Spassky-Petrosian from the 1969
World Championship Match}) 16. Qf4 $1 {[%csl Yd6] The d6-square is very
important in such positions, as after an exchange on d5, White would be able
to advance the pawn one step ahead. There's also the threat of Bxf7+.} Qe7 {
This move looks pretty natural, but it leads to a slightly unpleasant endgame
for Black.} (16... Qb8 $1 {[%csl Gd6] fighting for the d6-square should be
better.}) 17. Nd4 $1 {A move that puts some problems for Black.} (17. Rfe1 {
Also gave a tiny advantage for White in a rapid game} Rad8 18. h4 Bxd5 (18...
Rfe8 $142) 19. exd5 Qd6 20. Qe3 Nd7 21. Ng5 Nf6 22. Ne4 Nxe4 23. Qxe4 $14 {
[%csl Yd5] ;Le Quang Liem (2737)-Kravtsiv,M (2672) World Rapid 2017 (13.10) 1-0
}) 17... Bxd5 {Simplifying into an endgame in which White has a small
advantage.} (17... g6 $146 {was another option, but after, for example} 18.
Rfe1 Rad8 19. Nf3 Rfe8 20. h4 $5 {White has some ideas on the kingside.
Probably Black is fine, but practice will have to show how good White's
position really is.}) 18. exd5 Qe4 {Now, after} 19. Qxe4 Nxe4 20. Nc6 $1 {
[%csl Gc6,Yd5] The team d5+Nc6 considerably restricts Black's position, thus
giving White some advantage in this endgame.} Nd6 21. f3 $1 {Bringing the king
to the action.} Rfe8 22. Kf2 Kf8 23. Rd3 b5 $6 {Black tries to make use of his
queenside majority.} 24. a4 $1 {But this gives White a good chance of creating
some pressure and open lines there.} a6 25. Ra1 Rec8 26. g4 $1 {Since Black's
position is a bit paralyzed White takes time to make improvements and seize
some space on the kingside too.} g6 27. Ke3 $5 {[%cal Ye3c5] Now White
threatens to make serious improvements as his idea is to activate the king by
invading Black's queenside. This practically forces Black to seize the only
resource available.} ({Instead,} 27. Ra2 $1 {would have prevented this idea,
with good prospects}) 27... Nc4+ 28. Kd4 Nb2 {[%csl Ya4,Yd3] White still kept
some advantage thanks to a tactical idea:} 29. axb5 $1 Nxd3 30. b6 $1 {[%cal
Gb6b7]} Rab8 $8 (30... Nf4 31. b7 Re8 32. Kc5 $1 Rab8 33. Nxb8 Rxb8 34. Kb6
Nxd5+ 35. Ka7 $18) (30... Rcb8 31. Rxa6 $1 Rxa6 32. Nxb8 Ra1 (32... Ra8 33. Nc6
{[%cal Gb6b7]}) 33. b7 Rb1 34. Nd7+ Ke7 35. b8=Q Rxb8 36. Nxb8 $16) 31. Nxb8
Rxb8 32. Kxd3 $2 {White missed a nice alternative.} (32. Rb1 $1 {was very
annoying for Black} Nf2 (32... Nc1 33. Kc5 $1 {[%cal Yc5c6,Yc6c7,Gb6b7,Gc5b6,
Gb6a7]}) (32... Nf4 33. Ke5 Nd3+ 34. Kd6) 33. Kc5 $1 Nd3+ 34. Kd6 Rd8+ 35. Kc7
Ke7 36. b7 Rd7+ 37. Kb6 Rd8 38. Ka7 $16 {White should be winning}) 32... Rxb6
33. Kc4 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc4c5] White still has some chances, but
objectively Black should hold the endgame with precise play.} Ke7 34. Kc5 $6 {
A bit inaccurate.} (34. Ra3 $1 {would be prophylatical and good, if} Kd6 35. g5
$1 {and Black will be always in a sort of Zugzwang, allowing White to make
further improvements} Kc7 36. Kc5 Rb5+ 37. Kd4 Rb6 38. Ke5 $16) 34... Rf6 $2 {
Too passive, after this Black has problems again.} (34... Rb3 $1 {was the
right way, as in rook endgames it is very important get the rook as active as
possible} 35. f4 Rc3+ $1 {forcing the White king to go back} 36. Kd4 Rc2 37.
Rxa6 Rd2+ $1 38. Kc5 Rc2+ $1 39. Kb5 Rb2+ 40. Kc6 Rc2+ {and it is a draw
thanks to the rook activity}) 35. Ra3 Kd7 $2 (35... g5 $1 {[%csl Yf6] was
needed, preserving the rook in its ideal position}) 36. g5 $16 Rd6 (36... Rf5
37. Rxa6 Rxf3 38. Ra7+ Ke8 39. Kd6 {and White is winning}) 37. Rb3 Kc7 $2 {
When the pressure came, Black defended pretty badly.} (37... Ke7 38. Ra3 Kd7
39. f4 Ke7 40. Re3+ Kd7 41. Rh3 $18) 38. Rb7+ $1 {White found a nice way to
convert his positional advantage by forcing a winning queen endgame.} Kxb7 39.
Kxd6 $18 a5 40. Ke7 a4 41. d6 a3 42. d7 a2 43. d8=Q a1=Q {Both sides promote
their pawns, but White is the first one to give the checks, and his king is
also very active, winning Black pawns one by one.} 44. Qd5+ Kb6 45. Qd6+ Kb7
46. Kxf7 Qc3 47. Qd5+ Kb6 48. Kg8 Qc7 49. h4 Qe7 50. Qf7 Qe1 51. Kxh7 1-0

