1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 $5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Qxd5 6. e3 e5 $1 {
In the Chigorin Defense, Black goes for immediate pressure against the center.}
7. Nc3 Bb4 {Black should part with the bishop pair to continue with fast
development and to keep the position active.} 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {This
position is one of the tabyias of this opening, and much depends on the
strategy adopted by both sides from now. White's position, at first sight,
looks great and easy to play, with a mass of central pawns, supported by the
bishop pair, and open lines for his pieces. But appearances can be deceptive,
and White should be cautious: He is still behind in development, and any wrong
advances by the pawns would leave weak squares in his camp which Black would
be more than glad to occupy with the knights.} Qd6 $1 {Anticipating c4-d5
ideas.} (9... exd4 $6 {Is the second most played, but to be honest I don't
like this approach as I think that keeping the central tension is in Black's
interest.}) (9... Qd7 {was played recently by Rapport, but after} 10. Rb1 O-O-O
11. Bg2 Nge7 {Nakamura,H (2785)-Rapport,R (2692) Sharjah FIDE GP 2017 (3) 1-0}
12. f4 $1 exf4 13. O-O $1 $44 {White has excellent compensation by the pawn
sacrifice}) (9... Nge7 $2 {is simply bad as after} 10. c4 $1 Qd6 11. d5 $1 Nb8
12. Rb1 $36 {[%cal Yd2b4] White becomes very active}) (9... Nf6 $6 {is similar
to 9...Nge7} 10. c4 $1 Qd6 11. d5 $1 Ne7 12. Rb1 $36) 10. Bg2 ({the move order
} 10. Rb1 b6 11. f4 $1 exf4 12. e4 $1 {is most often seen, and probably most
precise. After} Nge7 13. Qf3 O-O (13... Ng6 14. h4 $1 Rd8 15. h5 Nge5 16. Qxf4
$18) 14. Bxf4 Qa3 15. Bg2 {we reach the same position as in the game, without
giving active chances for Black}) 10... Nge7 11. Rb1 {Usually this is a good
move as it forces some commitments in Black's position.} b6 (11... O-O-O 12. f4
$1 exf4 13. O-O $36) {The following idea is very nice and should be remembered:
} 12. f4 $1 exf4 13. e4 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Yd1f3,Gd2f4] This is the right
plan to put White's pawns in movement, without leaving weak squares in his
camp. Now, the position seems to offer a great potential to White's bishop
pair, but it is important to remember that White is still behind in
development.} (13. O-O $5 {was also interesting}) 13... O-O 14. Qf3 Qa3 $5 {
Black's attempt of counterplay on the queenside is useless, as White is more
than fine finishing the development by sacrificing the a2-pawn.} ({better was} 
14... Ng6 15. h4 (15. e5 $2 Ncxe5 $1 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxa8 Rxa8 18. Bxa8 Qd3
$1 $19 {[%cal Rf4f3]}) 15... Rad8 $1 $13 16. h5 $2 Nge5 $1 {this is the sort
of problems that White can face being behind in development.}) 15. Bxf4 Ng6 (
15... Qxa2 {wins the pawn, but the queen is misplaced now} 16. O-O Ng6 17. Bg3
$1 (17. Bxc7 Nh4 $1) 17... Na5 18. h4 $1 c6 19. h5 Ne7 20. h6 $1 $36 {gives a
pleasant initiative for White on the kingside.}) (15... f5 16. O-O Kh8 $6 (
16... Ng6 $2 17. exf5 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 Qxc3 19. Rbc1 {[%csl Rc6]} Nxd4 20. Rxc3
Ne2+ 21. Kh1 Nxf4 22. Bxa8 Rxa8 23. Rxc7 $18) 17. d5 $1 Ng6 (17... Na5 18. Bxc7
$18 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5d8]}) 18. Bc1 $1 $18 {Gershon,A (2562)-Pirrot,D (2421)
Bayern-chI Bank Hofmann 6th 2002 (5) 1-0} Qxa2 19. Rb2 Qc4 20. dxc6 {with a
technically won position}) 16. Bg3 {[%csl Yh4] Preventing Nh4.} f5 $5 {[%cal
Yf5e4,Yf5f4] Black should play as actively as he can and try to make use of
his development lead. Otherwise, White's advantage would become evident.
Despite this, the position looks a bit scary for White, but he can obtain an
advantage with the nice move:} 17. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Yd3c4]} ({Instead,} 17. exf5
$2 {played the initiative into Black's hands after} Rae8+ 18. Kf1 Nce7 19. Bh3
Qxa2 $36 {Tomczak,M (2395)-Lalith,B (2530) Warsaw Najdorf Memorial op-A 15th
2017 (7) 0-1}) 17... Nxd4 $5 {The best practical chance.} (17... f4 18. Qc4+
Kh8 19. Qxc6 fxg3 20. hxg3 Qxa2 21. O-O $16 {seems clearly better for White}) (
17... Qxa2 {leads to a forced variation:} 18. exf5 $1 Rae8+ 19. Be4 $1 {
which is better for White, for example} Rxf5 (19... Qd5 20. f3 Qxf5 21. O-O $18
{[%cal Ye4c6,Ye4f5,Gd3c4]}) 20. O-O Rf6 21. Rbe1 {[%cal Ye4d5]} Nce7 22. d5 Qa4
23. Bxc7 $16 {[%csl Yd5] and the passed pawn gives a nice advantage for White})
18. Qc4+ $1 {A necessary intermediate check, to take on d4 with the pawn.} Kh8
19. cxd4 Qa5+ $6 (19... f4 {regains the piece, but White is enjoying his
advantage after} 20. O-O fxg3 21. hxg3 c5 22. Rb3 $1 Qxa2 23. d5 Rac8 24. Qc3
$1 {[%cal Yb3a3]} Qa4 25. Ra3 Qd7 26. f4 b5 27. Qa1 $1 Rc7 28. e5 $16 {[%csl
Yd5,Ye5] the central passed pawns are always stronger and very powerful}) 20.
Ke2 $2 {There was no necessity to leave the king in such an exposed position.}
({a much better and forcing option was} 20. Qb4 $1 Qxb4+ (20... Qxa2 21. Bxc7
Qf7 22. Bg3 (22. Bd6 Nh4 $5) 22... f4 23. O-O fxg3 24. hxg3 $16 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4]
}) 21. Rxb4 f4 22. O-O fxg3 23. hxg3 {White's edge is out of the question here:
He has a strong centre, and the pawns might advance at any moment. Furthermore,
White can exert annoying pressure against Black's queenside. One possible
continuation could be} c6 24. Rc1 Ne7 25. e5 Rac8 26. Rbc4 b5 27. Rc5 $16 {
[%csl Gc6]}) 20... f4 21. e5 $6 ({more advisable was} 21. Rb5 Qa3 22. Qb3 {
when White is fighting to end Black's initiative} Qa6 {[%cal Yc7c6]} 23. Rc1 $1
Rac8 24. Ke1 $13) 21... Rae8 $2 {Playing again into White hands.} (21... Rad8
$1 {[%cal Yc7c5,Gd8d2]} 22. Be4 Nxe5 $1 $19) 22. Be4 $1 {White is better again.
} Nxe5 (22... fxg3 23. hxg3 $18 {[%cal Gh1h8]}) 23. dxe5 Qxe5 24. f3 fxg3 25.
hxg3 h6 {White is simply a piece up and winning with correct play, but somehow
he didn't solve his problems and even lost the game.} 26. Rhg1 Rf6 27. Rb5 (27.
Rbe1 $142 {[%cal Ye2f2,Yf2g2]}) 27... c5 28. Rbb1 Qh5 29. Kf2 Qg4 30. Qd5 $4 {
A huge blunder.} (30. Rge1 {is the right move, as} Rxf3+ $2 {is met by} 31.
Bxf3 Qxc4 32. Rxe8+ $18) 30... Qxe4 $19 31. Qxe4 Rxe4 32. Rgd1 Re7 33. a4 Kg8
34. a5 Kf7 35. Rd8 Rc7 36. Rb8 bxa5 37. R8b5 c4 38. Rxa5 c3 39. Rc1 c2 40. Ra2
Rfc6 41. Ke2 Rc3 42. g4 g6 43. Ra6 R3c6 44. Ra2 Kf6 45. Ra5 Rc5 46. Ra2 h5 47.
gxh5 gxh5 48. Kf2 Kf5 49. Kg3 h4+ 50. Kf2 Kf4 51. Ra4+ Rc4 52. Ra5 Rc3 53. Ra4+
R7c4 54. Rxa7 Rxf3+ 55. Kg2 h3+ 56. Kh2 Ke3 57. Rd7 Ke2 58. Rd8 Rd3 59. Re8+
Kd2 60. Ree1 Kc3 0-1

