1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 ({the common move order is} 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5.
a3 $1) 2... Nc6 3. c4 e5 $5 (3... Bg4 {is the Chigorin Defense}) 4. dxe5 d4 5.
a3 $1 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gb2b4] A move that not just prevents the check on b4,
but also prepares to follow with b4-b5, weakening the d4-pawn.} (5. e3 {
would be perfect if Black did not have} Bb4+ 6. Bd2 dxe3 $1 {with already an
easier game}) 5... Nge7 (5... a5 {There's no time to stop White's expansion on
the queenside:} 6. e3 $1 {since the check was prevented now}) 6. b4 {[%cal
Yb4b5,Gc1b2]} Ng6 7. Bb2 a5 $1 {This is played to force some advances in
White's position, but although it is a more precise way to play before taking
on e5, it is not enough to equalize.} ({anyway, after} 7... Ncxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5
9. e3 $1 Be6 $8 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. Qc2 Nd6 12. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3,Yd4] White's
advantage is also very pleasant}) 8. b5 Ncxe5 9. Qxd4 $5 {Despite not being
the most played option, I think the endgames that arise by force are much
easier for White, with a good pressure against Black's queenside and no risk.}
(9. Nxe5 {is the main move} Nxe5 10. e3 Be6 11. Bxd4 Nxc4 12. Qc2 Nd6 {is
similar to the game, but here Black managed to get rid of the misplaced Ng6,
and some games show that with queens on board Black can dream of counterplay
chances. Of course, White is still ahead, but I think the endgame provides a
free of risk advantage and is very easy to work}) 9... Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11.
e3 Nd6 (11... Be6 12. Ng5 $1 {is unpleasant for Black}) 12. Nbd2 {[%cal Ya1c1,
Yc1c7,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White has more than one way to create problems for Black
here, but the main issue is that such positions are not the sort of play that
Albin's players are looking for.} Bd7 (12... a4 $2 {seems natural, fixing
White's queenside pawns, but wastes some precious time} 13. Rc1 Kd8 (13... Nf5
{[%csl Ya3]} 14. Bb2 $18) 14. h4 $1 {White makes an instructive use of his
strategical plusses} h5 15. Bd3 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Ng5 $1 Nh6 (17... Bxa3
18. Nxf7+ Kd7 19. Nxh8 Bxc1 20. Nxg6 $18) 18. Nc4 Ke8 19. Bb2 $16 {Bluebaum,M 
(2643)-Trent,L (2435) Bundesliga 2017-18 (11.4) 1-0 Black is very cramped on
the kingside, and White had a comfortable advantage in}) (12... Nf5 13. Bb2 $16
{[%cal Ya1c1,Gh2h4,Gh4h5]}) 13. a4 Nf5 {Black has also tried another option
here, although none of them managed to solve his problems.} (13... b6 $2 {
seems simply bad, fixing the c7-pawn as a permanent target} 14. Bd3 f6 15. O-O
Be7 16. Rfc1 Rc8 17. Rc2 $1 O-O 18. Rac1 Bd8 19. Bb2 $1 $16 {[%cal Yb2a3] ;
Macedo,M (2357)-Albuquerque,W (2168) Joao Pessoa Fischer Memorial 8th 2017 (6)
1-0 and Black is in big trouble -}) (13... c6 $5 {seems also natural, getting
rid of the c7-pawn} 14. bxc6 Bxc6 15. Bc3 $5 {preventing b7-b5} f6 16. Be2 Be7
17. O-O O-O {Scott,G (2198)-Larsen,A (1976) Hastings Masters op 92nd 2016 (5)
1/2 White would have preserved an advantage now through} 18. Nc4 $1 Nxc4 19.
Bxc4+ Kh8 20. Be6 $1 $14 {[%cal Yf3d4,Gf1d1,Gd1b1]}) (13... f6 14. Be2 Ne7 $2 {
this manoeuvre was too slow} 15. O-O Nd5 16. Rfc1 c6 17. bxc6 Bxc6 18. Bc5 Nf5
19. Nb3 Nb4 20. Bb6 $18 {[%csl Ra5] ;Peralta,F (2574)-Perez Candelario,M (2496)
Iberoamerican-ch GpC 1st 2006 (5) 1-0}) 14. Bc3 Bb4 $6 {There's no easy way to
continue Black's development.} (14... f6 15. Bd3 Bd6 16. Be4 $1 c6 17. Nc4 Bc7
18. Rd1 $1 {and Black is under annoying pressure}) 15. Bxb4 axb4 16. Bd3 {
[%csl Gb4][%cal Ye1e2,Yh1b1] Black has serious problems with the b4-pawn Now,
and after the forced c7-c5, he is also creating weaknesses on the queenside.}
Nd6 (16... O-O 17. O-O c5 {Rodriguez Lopez,R (2244)-Revilla Rio,F (2127)
ESP-chT CECLUB Div1 Final Permanencia 2012 (1.4) 1-0} 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Nb3 {
White establishes a firm blockade against Black's queenside pawns, with a
stable advantage} Nd6 20. Rfc1 Rfd8 21. Nc5 Bf5 22. Bxf5 Nxf5 23. a5 $16) (
16... Ke7 {is an option} 17. Ke2 c5 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Bxf5 $1 {a very
well-timed exchange, as White keeps the two knights to exploit the weak
dark-squares on Black's queenside, and the bishop will be useless in this fight
} Bxf5 20. Nd4 Bd7 21. Rhc1 Rhc8 22. N2b3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc1c4,Yb3c5,Ya4a5]
White has a very nice advantage here, and it seems unlikely the Black will be
able to withstand the increasing pressure.}) 17. Ke2 c5 (17... Ne7 $1 {was a
better move} 18. Nc4 $1 (18. Rhb1 Nd5 {[%cal Yd5c3]}) 18... Nd5 19. Nxd6+ cxd6
20. Kd2 Nc3 21. Nd4 {and White keeps the advantage} Rxa4 (21... O-O 22. a5 $16)
22. Rxa4 Nxa4 23. Ra1 Nb6 24. Ra7 Bc8 25. Kc2 {[%cal Yc2b3] With some pressure
for White, although it seems that with correct play Black should hold} (25. Nc2
Kd8 26. Nxb4 Kc7 27. Ra1)) 18. bxc6 bxc6 (18... Bxc6 $142 19. Rhb1 Rxa4 20.
Rxa4 Bxa4 21. Rxb4 Bc6 22. Nd4 $1 Bxg2 23. f3 $36 {[%cal Yd2e4]}) 19. Nb3 Ke7
20. Rhc1 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Yb4,Yc6] Once that this position is reached, it is
clear that White is better: He is not only blocking but also soon exerting
pressure against Black's queenside pawns, and the distant passed pawn is also
a worthy advantage. Black's defense is very unpleasant and difficult from now.}
Rhc8 21. Nc5 Bf5 22. Nd4 $1 Bxd3+ 23. Nxd3 {[%csl Rc6] The last exchange left
the c6-pawn unprotected.} Kd7 24. Rab1 Rab8 (24... Rxa4 $4 25. Nc5+) 25. Nc5+
Ke8 26. Nc2 {[%csl Rb4] The pawn is lost and also is the game.} Nb7 27. Nxb7
Rxb7 28. Rxb4 Rxb4 29. Nxb4 $18 Ra8 30. Ra1 Ne7 31. e4 Ra5 32. Kd3 Kd7 33. Kc3
Nc8 34. Nd3 c5 35. Ne5+ Ke6 36. Nc4 Ra6 37. a5 Ne7 38. Rb1 f5 39. f3 fxe4 40.
fxe4 Nc6 41. Rb5 Ne5 42. Rxc5 1-0

