1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 ({the main move order is} 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5.
Nf3) 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 $5 {This move characterizes the famous Tarrasch
Variation of the QGD, a line that has been regularly played along the chess
history, even used as a weapon by Garry Kasparov in some moments of his career.
Right from the opening Black looks for a dynamic play in center and tries to
gain space for his pieces. As we know, this is not the case in the typical QGD
positions in which Black accepts a solid position but slightly passive
position.} 5. cxd5 {The correct reaction - White isolates the d5-pawn which
becomes the main point of his strategy.} exd5 (5... cxd4 $5 {[%emt 0:00:02]
This move is covered in Chapter 3}) (5... Nxd5 {[%emt 0:00:04] is dealt with
in Chapter 4-6.}) 6. g3 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yf1g2] Although other options are
also playable for White, 6.g3 always seemed like the most principled plan to
me. It is hard to imagine a better place for this bishop since from g2 it
protects the kingside and exerts a strong pressure against d5.} Nc6 7. Bg2 Be7
({In some games, Black tried a more active development with} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
Bc5 {but White still can keep an advantage. For example, after} 9. Nb3 Bb4 ({
After} 9... Bb6 {, White can accept the challenge and take the pawn} 10. Nxd5
$5 O-O 11. O-O Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxd5 Bg4 14. Re1 Nb4 $1 15. Bxb7 $1 Rae8
16. Bf4 $1 $13 {[%cal Yf4d6]}) 10. O-O Be6 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Yc1]
[%cal Yc1a3,Yc1g5] is better for White as his dark-squared bishop will be very
strong.}) 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Rc1 {White develops his pieces in s simple way and
has already a good position while Black didn't achieve any concrete advantage
compared to the mains lines.} Rc8 13. Rc2 $5 {[%csl Yb2] protecting b2 and
threatening Bxf6 followed by Nxd5. Later on, the rook can be shifted to d2, if
necessary.} d4 $2 {Almeida Quintana,O (2521)-Murillo,O (1759) Bogota Navidad
op 2016 (1) 1-0} 14. Rd2 $1 {[%csl Yd4] Black faces big problems now} Bxb3 15.
axb3 h6 {Now, White just wins a pawn with} (15... Bc5 16. e3 $1) 16. Bxf6 Qxf6
17. Nd5 Qd6 18. Nxb4 Qxb4 19. Bxc6 Rxc6 20. Rxd4 $14) 8. O-O O-O (8... Be6 {
is a different move, but it doesn't change the character of the arising
positions.}) ({Sometimes, Black tries to close the center by means of} 8... c4
{Usually, the advance c5-c4 is not played exactly in this move order. In
general, Black plays this after 8...0-0 9.Bg5 c4. In our main line, however,
this option will not be allowed. That is why the only moment in which this
move is worth considering is now.} 9. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ye5c6] After c5-c4, it
becomes very difficult to create pressure against d5, so White intends to
change the structure with Nxc6 followed by b2-b3, subsequently transmitting
the pressure to the recently created weak pawn on c6.} O-O {Now 10.Bg5, would
transpose to one of the main lines, but I like the immediate} 10. b3 $5 cxb3 (
10... Qa5 11. Bb2 Bb4 12. Rc1 cxb3 13. axb3 Be6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Na4 $14 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc1c6] Khenkin,I (2638)-Vilar Lopez,M (2145) Andorra op 21st
2003 (1) 1-0 With typical positional advantage for White.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
axb3 a5 13. Ba3 $1 {This is a nice detail about keeping the bishop on c1.
White can force Black to trade off his best bishop which is an important
strategic achievement. After} Re8 14. Qc2 Ba6 {Svane,R (2445)-Zieher,H (2300)
GER-ch 84th Saarbruecken 2013 (3) 1-0, the simple} 15. Bxe7 $1 {would leave
White with a pleasant advantage. Here is how the game might continue:} Rxe7 (
15... Qxe7 16. Rxa5 Bd3 $5 17. Qa2 $1 Rxa5 18. Qxa5 $16 Bxe2 $2 19. Re1 {
[%csl Re2]}) 16. Rfc1 {[%cal Ye2e3,Gc3a4] White threatens to continue with
e2-e3 and Na4, which gives him a definite advantage, and if Black goes for
some active idea like} Rc8 17. e3 c5 {, it just increases White's advantage
after} 18. Bh3 $1 Rc6 (18... Rcc7 19. Qd2 {[%cal Ya1a5]} cxd4 20. Qxd4 $16 {
[%csl Ra5,Rd5]}) 19. Na4 $1 c4 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. Bf1 $1 cxb3 22. Qxb3 $16 {
and Black's position remains difficult.}) 9. dxc5 {This is a relatively simple
way to play with White. The idea is to initiate play against the immediately
Isolani. This is also an effective approach since White doesn't have to deal
with the variations in which Black goes for the advance c5-c4.} Bxc5 10. Na4 (
10. a3 {[%cal Yb2b4,Yc1b2] used to be another good option, but recently Black
has proven that the sacrifice} Ne4 $1 {should be enough to get equality}) 10...
Be7 11. Be3 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4][%cal Ya1c1] The plan is very clear: White should
establish firm control over the important squares around the isolani when
especially important is the blockade on d4. Additionally, the squares c5, e5,
and even f4 can be comfortably occupied by White's forces. That is why White
will be trying to exchange Black's dark-squared bishop. Bringing the rooks to
c1 and d1 is a likely follow-up as well. As a general rule, Black should
decide whether to safely protect the pawn and accept a passive position, or
opt for active actions which are always very risky. This is the kind of
position in which is better to understand the typical ideas, pawn structures
and exchanges than memorizing moves. Black has tried many moves in this
position. None of them, however, manages to change the character of the game.
Also, various transpositions are possible. That is why we are going to
investigate the three most popular and logical moves.} Re8 {[%cal Ge8e1] This
is the most popular continuation. Black occupies the important e-file and is
ready to sacrifice an exchange on e3 under favorable circumstances.} (11... Bg4
{is the second most played option which is also very logical. The side who has
the isolani should develop his forces as active as possible.} 12. Rc1 Rc8 (
12... Qd7 13. Nc5 $1 {This move is forcing some favourable exchanges for White.
The play may continue} Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Rfe8 15. Re1 {[%cal Yf3d4] with a
transposition to the main line.}) (12... Re8 {transposes to the main line}) 13.
h3 Bh5 14. Nc5 $1 {This move creates a difficult choice for Black - give away
the bishop or weaken the queenside by playing b7-b6. He preferred the first one
} Bxc5 15. Rxc5 {[%csl Ye3,Yg2] but now many endgames are easier for White due
to the bishop pair.} b6 16. Rc1 Qd7 17. g4 $5 {White keeps gradually improving
his position.} Bg6 18. Nd4 h5 19. g5 Ne4 20. Nxc6 Rxc6 21. Qa4 $1 Rfc8 22. Rxc6
Rxc6 23. Rd1 Rd6 24. Qxd7 Rxd7 25. h4 $14 {[%cal Yf2f3] ;L'Ami,E (2615)
-Akobian,V (2628) Corus-B Wijk aan Zee 2010 (4) 1-0 and the two bishops proved
their strength in this endgame.}) (11... Ne4 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ye7f6] This move
takes the c5-square under control and prepares the activation of the
dark-squared bishop via f6. White obtained a nice advantage in some games with
the move} 12. Nd4 {In this structure, the exchanges are always good for White.}
Ne5 13. Rc1 Bd7 ({Even the great Capablanca has an instructive example in this
position} 13... Qa5 14. Bf4 Ng6 15. Bc7 $1 Qa6 {Now, the queen is badly placed}
16. a3 {White anticipates Black's next move} Bd7 17. Nc3 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Be6 19.
b4 $18 {Capablanca, J-Znosko Borovsky,E Paris 1938 (4) 1-0 and White is
already winning, as simple as in many Capablanca's games -}) 14. Bf4 $1 (14.
Nc3 {direct is also good}) 14... Bd6 (14... Ng6 15. Bc7 $1 {a similar idea to
the one that we have seen in Capablanca's game.} Qe8 16. Nc3 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 $16)
(14... Nc6 15. Nb5 $1) 15. Nc3 $1 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 $16 {[%csl Yd5] and White had
a clear advantage in Mareco,S (2583)-Barrionuevo,P (2318) Moron Panno Masters
1st 2012 (8) 1-0}) 12. Rc1 Bg4 (12... Ne4 13. Nd4 Bd7 14. Nc3 $1 {Again, White
forces exchanges which are good for White} Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Bf6 16. Re1 $14 {
Malakhov,V (2670)-Larino Nieto,D (2325) Benidorm op rap 2nd rapid 2005 (3) 1-0}
) 13. Nc5 (13. h3 $5 {is an interesting move, forcing Black to clarify the
position of his bishop.Nevertheless, Black manages to get a good position with}
Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qd7 15. Bg2 Rad8 {Now, Black is better prepared for} 16. Nc5 Bxc5
17. Bxc5 Ne4 18. e3 Qf5 {and Black's well-centralized pieces compensate the
isolated pawn -Bok,B (2607)-Batsiashvili,N (2485) Tata Steel-B 78th 2016 (6) 1/
2-1/2}) 13... Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Qd7 15. Re1 {[%cal Yf3d4] White is ready to play
Nd4 and keep making exchanges that will lead to a better endgame, where the
bishop pair becomes very strong. So, it makes sense for Black to play actively
with} Bh3 (15... Rad8 $6 {doesn't prevent White's idea} 16. Nd4 Rc8 $2 {
the only acceptable excuse to waste time like this, is that it was a blitz game
} 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bd4 Qe6 {Roiz,M (2600)-Demuth,A (2545) Wch Blitz 9th blitz
2015 (15) 1-0} 19. Qa4 $16 {[%csl Ga7,Gc6]}) (15... Bf5 $6 {was also bad} 16.
Nd4 Be4 17. f3 $1 Bg6 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Qa4 Rec8 20. Rc3 $16 {Nyback, T (2586)
-Leito,P (2333) Puhajarve rap op 14th rapid 2013 (16) 1-0}) (15... Rac8 {
looks natural. Black tries to avoid the immediate Nd4, but White can play} 16.
Bd4 $5 Ne4 (16... Nxd4 17. Qxd4 $1 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 {Annakov,B (2565)-Akobian,
V (2438) Abu Dhabi op 10th 2000 (4) 1/2-1/2} 19. Rxc8+ Qxc8 20. h3 $5 {this
move could offer some chances, trading the h3-pawn for the one on a7. On the
other hand, the move} Bd7 {is well met by} 21. Ne5 $14) 17. Be3 $1 {[%cal
Yf3d4] after this Bd4-e3 maneuver, White is prepared to play Nd4} h5 $5 {
Pigusov,E (2455)-Lputian,S (2530) Chigorin Memorial-19 1985 1/2-1/2} 18. Qa4
Bh3 19. Bxh3 Qxh3 20. Qb3 Qd7 21. Red1 Red8 22. Kg2 $14) 16. Bh1 $1 {This
retreat also seems very natural.} Ne4 (16... Rad8 17. Nd4 $1 Ne4 18. Nxc6 bxc6
19. Bd4 Rc8 20. Qa4 $1 Rc7 21. Qa5 $1 {[%csl Yc5] and White has a firm control
over the c5 - square. Gheorghiu,F (2535)-Nykopp,J (2230) Bern op 1988 1-0}) 17.
Be3 Rad8 {As we have seen in some variations, this move is not useful as Black
can't prevent Nd4.} 18. Nd4 (18. Qa4 $5 d4 $2 (18... Qg4 $1 $13) 19. Nxd4 $1
Nxd4 20. Qxd7 Rxd7 21. Bxe4 $16 {White simply won a pawn - Mindlin,A (2450)
-Novik,M (2482) Maccabiah GM-B 2017 (4) 1-0}) 18... Ne5 19. Bf4 (19. f3 $5 {
Zagorskis,D (2468)-Warszawski,B (2275) Warsaw AIG Life rapid 6th 2006 (4) 1-0})
19... Qe7 (19... h6 20. Bxe5 $1 Rxe5 21. e3 Ree8 22. Qe2 a6 23. Rc2 Rc8 24.
Rec1 Rxc2 25. Qxc2 $14 {Such positions are always unpleasant to play for the
defending side. Finally, White managed to win in Gheorghiu,F (2530)-Lalic, B 
(2440) Mendrisio op 1985 1-0}) 20. Bxe5 $1 {This exchange leads to a position
with practical chances and no risk for White.} Qxe5 21. e3 Rd6 $5 {Looking for
