1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 $5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. g3 $1 {[%csl Gd5]
[%cal Yf1g2]} Nc6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. dxc5 d4 $5 {This is a very
interesting pawn sacrifice. The critical position arises after the moves} 10.
Na4 Bf5 {Black plays in a dynamic way and has an easier development in return
to the pawn. Additionally, White's Na4 is a bit misplaced. Nevertheless, a
pawn is a pawn, and I believe that with correct play White is able to
neutralize Black's active attempts and remain a pawn up.} (10... Bg4 $2 {
is a mistake due to} 11. b4 $1 {which gives White a big advantage.}) 11. a3 $5
{[%cal Yb2b4,Gc1b2] White is planning to follow with b2-b4 and Bb2. In this
way, he protects the pawn and continues the development.} (11. b4 {is still
playable, but Black can complicate matters with} d3 $1 {Probably, White still
keeps better chances here, but such positions tend to become a mess. If you
have a safer option, it is advisable to go for it.}) 11... Be4 (11... Ne4 {
looks pretty logical, as after} 12. b4 {[%csl Yc3] Black can create a strong
passed pawn with Nc3} Bf6 (12... Nc3 $146 {strangely, this move was never
played, probably because of} 13. Nxc3 dxc3 14. Qb3 Bf6 15. Be3 {White's
dark-squared bishop is alive which is clearly in White's favor.}) 13. Bb2 Nc3 {
In this way, Black gets the bishop pair, but White can quickly organize his
pieces to attack the c3-pawn.} 14. Bxc3 dxc3 15. Qb3 c2 16. Rac1 Re8 17. Nc3 {
[%cal Ye2e4] and it becomes clear that Black is unable to support the pawn} a5
(17... Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Rxe2 19. b5 $18 {[%cal Gf3d4]}) 18. b5 $1 a4 (18... Nd4
19. Nxd4 Qxd4 20. e4 $1 {guarantees White's advantage}) 19. Qd5 $1 Ne7 20. Qxd8
Rexd8 21. e4 $1 {Now, White manages to eliminate the pawn while keeping the
material advantage} Rac8 22. exf5 Bxc3 23. Rxc2 Rxc5 24. Rfc1 Rdc8 25. Ne1 $1
$16 {L'Ami,E (2627)-Berelowitsch,A (2565) NED-chT 1213 2012 (7.1) 1-0}) ({
Against} 11... d3 12. Re1 $1 {is an adequate response. A possible continuation
is} dxe2 13. Qxe2 Qa5 14. Qc4 Be6 15. Rxe6 $1 {A well-timed exchange sacrifice}
fxe6 16. Bd2 Qd8 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 {Demir,G (2239)-Adams,N (2205) Budapest FS12 IM
2008 (5) 1/2-1/2} 18. Be3 $16 {White has a pawn up on both wings, better
pieces, and Black's king is weak. This is more than sufficient compensation
for the exchange.}) 12. b4 Qd5 {Black opts for a full centralization of his
forces, but White's position is still excellent.} 13. Bf4 g5 $5 (13... h6 $2 {
was too slow} 14. Rc1 g5 15. Bd6 $1 $16 {Kovalyov,A (2617)-Shabalov,A (2529)
Foxwoods op Mashantucket 2014 (6) 1-0} Bxd6 16. cxd6 Qxd6 17. Nc5 {[%csl Yb7,
Ye4]}) 14. Bd2 $1 {Now the g5-pawn is also a weakness which requires attention}
Nd7 15. Nb2 Nce5 16. Nd3 $1 Nc4 {Benjamin,J (2255)-Todorovic,G (2410) London
Peace 1987 1/2-1/2} 17. Qb3 $16 {[%cal Ya1c1,Yf1d1] White is simply completing
development with a big advantage. For example:} Rfd8 (17... g4 $2 18. Nf4 $1
Nxd2 19. Nxd2 $18) 18. Rfd1 Bf6 19. Rac1 {White's advantage is obvious.} *

