1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 $5 {This move had been
popular for a certain period of time. Nowadays, however, this continuation is
not fashionable anymore.} 6. Qxd4 (6. Qa4+ {wins a pawn for White, but after}
Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 8. Nxd5 Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nc6 {Black has an excellent development
which compensates the missing pawn. That is exactly the sort of game he is
hoping for in this line. I see no reason to allow this.}) (6. Nxd4 Nxd5 {
is just harmless for Black}) 6... exd5 (6... Nxd5 $6 {looks a bit risky} 7. e4
$1 Nxc3 (7... Nc6 $2 {gives White an obvious advantage after} 8. Bb5 Nxc3 9.
Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 10. Qxc3 {[%csl Gc6] White has achieved a better pawn structure
and a lead in development. His advantage is obvious} Qb6 11. O-O Qc5 12. Qb3
Qb6 {Filippov,V (2584)-Yin, H (2496) Sufe Cup Shanghai 2000 (6) 1-0} 13. Qc2 $1
Qc5 14. Qb1 $1 {[%cal Yc1e3] and suddenly Black's position becomes very
difficult, for example} Be7 15. Be3 Qd6 16. Rd1 Qc7 17. Qc2 O-O 18. Nd4 Bb7 19.
Nb3 $1 $14 {[%cal Ye3c5]}) 8. Qxc3 Nc6 {[%cal Yf8b4]} 9. a3 Bd7 10. Be2 Rc8 {
Black's position looks active, but this nice Anand's game proves that it is
not true} 11. O-O Na5 12. Qd3 $1 Ba4 (12... Be7 13. b4 Nc6 14. Bb2 $16) 13.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Be3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Ge2,Ge3] Black's lack of development is
already telling} Nb3 (14... b6 15. Rac1 {[%cal Yc1c7]}) 15. Bd1 $1 b5 $2 (15...
a6 {also failed to solve Black's problems.} 16. Bxb3 Bxb3 17. Rac1 Bd6 18. Bb6
Ra8 19. Nd4 Ba4 20. Rc4 $1 {White starts to win many tempos hunting this bishop
} Bd7 21. Rd1 O-O 22. e5 $1 {and Black's position remains under annoying
pressure - Kramnik,V (2790)-Van Wely,L (2605) Amber-blindfold 07th rapid 1998 
(1) 1-0}) 16. Bxb3 $1 Bxb3 17. Rfc1 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Yc1c7] White is not only
attacking a7 and threatening Rc7. At the same time, the Bb3 is also terribly
misplaced.} e5 (17... a5 18. Nd2 a4 19. Nxb3 axb3 20. Rc3 $18 {[%csl Rb3,Rb5]})
18. Nxe5 $18 {Anand,V (2795)-Kortschnoj,V (2625) Tilburg Fontys 1998 (8) 1-0})
7. Bg5 {[%csl Yd5] This is my recommendation and I believe it is a reliable
option in the spirit of Tarrasch positions. White is aiming for a long
pressure against the Isolani. Sometimes, instead of long and forced variations,
it is better to keep the game going and develop your pieces. In general, such
positions are perfect for technical players. Even though Black is doing well
with a correct play, his position is a bit unpleasant, and from a practical
point of view, it is easier to play with White.} (7. e4 $5 {is the main move
which leads to a forced game and many simplifications. In the forced lines,
Black is doing quite reasonably, despite White having a small plus.} Nc6 8. Bb5
dxe4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Ng5 Be6 {White tried more than one idea to get some
advantage in this position, with and without the moves Bxc6 and Nxe6. As the
games in the database show, however, in all the lines, Black holds with a
correct play.}) 7... Be7 ({Of course, the move} 7... Nc6 $2 {is weak because
of the simple} 8. Bxf6 $1) (7... Be6 {was played in the game Sadorra,J (2300)
-Seet,C (2005) Cairnhill op 22nd 2004 (3) 1-0} 8. e4 $1 $146 {This move is
much more effective now. Curiously, this continuation may transpose to one of
the games of the great Emanuel Lasker.} Nc6 9. Bb5 dxe4 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qxe4
Rc8 12. O-O Be7 13. Nd4 {simply winning a pawn for White - Karosene,
A-Muslimova, A URS Club Team-ch 1968 (1.9) 1/2-1/2}) 8. e3 (8. Qa4+ {was seen
in a Ding Liren's game. Although this move was played only a few times, it
makes sense as in many positions after Nc6 the queen goes to a4.} Nc6 ({
the idea is to answer} 8... Bd7 {with} 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Yb7,Yd5]} Bc6 10. Rd1 {
and Black's set-up is not the best to play with an isolated pawn. Generally,
Black would put the knight on c6 and the bishop would remain on the diagonal
c8-h3.}) 9. e3 h6 (9... O-O 10. Rd1 Be6 {transposes to the main line}) 10. Bh4
O-O 11. Bb5 Ne4 $5 {Black trades off some pieces to remove any possible
pressure against the pawn. As we know, however, the exchanges are better for
the side that is playing against the isolani.} (11... Bd7 {Ding's game went}
12. O-O a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Ne5 $1 Qc7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Rfd1 Qb7 17. Qc2 Rfe8
18. Rac1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5][%cal Yc3a4] with a typical structure in which Black's
