A (2562) CRO-ch Porec 2014 (3) 1/2-1/2} 15. Nxe4 $5 {this could be an
improvement to keep chances, as the game continuation leads to a draw.} dxe4
16. Qxe4 Qxb5 (16... axb5 $6 17. Qxe7 Rxa2 18. Qe5 $1 $14 {[%cal Yc1c7,Yf1c1,
Gf3d4] should be easier to play with White}) 17. Qxe7 Qxb2 18. a3 Bf5 19. Rc7
b5 20. Qc5 {keeping some pressure with the pieces, although, objectively,
Black should be doing well.}) 8... Nc6 {Probably the most precise, as it cuts
some of White's options.} ({After} 8... O-O {, there are at least two
interesting games in which White achieved a great position} 9. Rd1 (9. Bd3 $5 {
this is an interesting move introduced by the always creative GM Nisipeanu} h6
10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qa4 Be6 (11... Qb6 $2 {[%csl Gb6] It is important to point out
that with the bishop on d3, this typical active move doesn't work.} 12. Bxf6
Bxf6 13. Nxd5 Qxb2 14. Rb1 $18 {[%csl Rb2] trapping the queen}) 12. O-O a6 {
Although this is not a bad move, the plan behind it doesn't look correct} (
12... Qb6 {now looks better. White can follow with} 13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Nxb5 {
when we reach a typical queenless middlegame with an isolani. The position is
probably equal, but White's chances are in the endgame. That is why such
positions can always be potentially dangerous.} Rac8 15. Rac1 Rfd8 (15... g5 $5
16. Bg3 Ne4 $132 {looks a reliable way to get counterplay for Black}) 16. Nbd4
Nxd4 17. Nxd4 a6 (17... g5 $6 {leads to further weaknesses on the kingside.}
18. Bg3 Ne4 19. Be5 $14) 18. Rfd1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Rc8 20. Rxc8+ Bxc8 {Rojicek,V 
(2450)-Hausner,I (2407) CZE-chT 1213 2012 (7.4) 1/2-1/2} 21. Nf5 $5 {Taking
the bishop pair looks a good option to provoke some unbalance in the endgame.}
Kf8 22. Nxe7 Kxe7 23. f3 $14 {[%cal Yh4e1,Ye1c3] with a pleasant advantage for
White.}) 13. Rad1 b5 $6 {Someone can argue that this move is not bad, but I
can not see how it helps Black. On the other hand, the advance b7-b5 creates
additional weaknesses on the queenside.} (13... Qb6 $142 14. Rd2 Rfd8 15. Rfd1
Rac8 16. Bb1 {White's prospects are slightly better but Black is very much in
the game.}) 14. Qc2 Rc8 (14... Nb4 15. Qb1 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 b4 17. Ne2 Bd7 {
[%cal Yd7b5]} 18. Qb1 $14 {[%cal Ge2d4]}) 15. Qb1 Qb6 16. Bf5 $1 {Strangely
enough, in this position, the exchange of the light-squared bishops favors
White. Indeed, from a theoretical point of view, the e6-bishop is week. In the
concrete position however, this bishop protects the isolated pawn and covers
an important complex of light squares.} Rcd8 17. Ne2 $1 {White threatens not
just Ned4 or Nf4 increasing the pressure against the Be6, but also Bxe6
followed by Qg6 and Nf4. Black is already in a difficult situation.} Bxf5 18.
Qxf5 Rd6 $6 {This unfortunate move helps White to improve the position of his
forces further.} 19. Bg3 Rd7 (19... Rdd8 $142) 20. Ne5 $1 {By means of this
exchange, White's dark-squared bishop will be transferred to the long diagonal.
