1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 b6 {This is a more flexible option
since the bishop should go to b7 anyway. With this move order, Black intends
to develop his knight according to White's plan.} 12. d5 $1 {With Black being
underdeveloped, this break is even more effective. My analysis shows that
Black can not completely solve his problems.} Na6 {Probably, this is Black's
best chance. He refrains from exchanging the bishops through Ba6. Even in this
case, however, the problems persist.} (12... Ba6 {is the most frequently
played move, but after} 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. d6 $14 {[%csl Gd6] the absence of
the light-squared bishops is in White's favour since Black has no way to
generate counterplay using the long diagonal. Additionally, White's central
passed pawn is powerful in this position.} Nc5 (14... f6 15. O-O (15. e5 fxe5
16. O-O Rf5 17. Rfe1 e4 18. Rxe4 Rd5 19. Qe2 Nc5 20. Rxe6 Rxd6 21. Re3 Rd3 22.
Re5 Rd7 23. Qc4+ Kh8 24. h4) 15... e5) 15. e5 Qd7 (15... f6 16. O-O Rf7 $5 {
[%cal Yf7d7] is an interesting idea with which Black achieved a draw in an old
game, but White's play can be improved Kortschnoj, V-Mecking,H Christmas
Congress 1971/72-47 Premier 1971 (8) 1/2-1/2} 17. Rfd1 Rd7 18. Rac1 Rc8 19. Rc4
$5 {[%cal Yc4d4,Yc4f4] and the rook creates some annoying threats along the
4th rank. Black remains under pressure.}) 16. O-O Rad8 17. Rad1 Qa4 18. Rfe1 {
The passed pawn gives White's pieces more space and mobility. Definitely,
White has an easy game in this position.} f6 $6 {This is a desperate attempt
to obtain a counterplay. At the same time, this move is quite risky because it
creates new weaknesses.} ({Of course, the waiting strategy wouldn't be enough
to keep Black safe. For example:} 18... Rd7 19. Qb2 Rc8 20. Rd4 Qc6 21. Rc4 h6
22. Rec1 {[%cal Yc1c8] Since Black doesn't open lines on the kingside, White
turns his attention to the c-file - the next step is to remove the c5-knight.}
Rdd8 23. Qe2 Kh8 24. Nd4 Qb7 25. Nb3 $1 Nxb3 26. axb3 Rxc4 27. Qxc4 $18 {
with a winning endgame}) 19. Qe2 fxe5 20. Nxe5 Rf4 21. d7 {[%csl Gd7] White is
winning} h6 22. g3 Rf5 (22... Re4 23. Qh5 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Nxd7 $2 25. Qf7+ Kh8
26. Qe7 $18) 23. Rd6 $18 {Caruana,F (2799)-Xiong,J (2633) Douglas IoM op 2017 
(5) 1-0}) (12... e5 $2 13. O-O $1 {White just ignores Black's attempts to
force complications.} Qd6 {Nie,X (2078)-Liu,M (2035) CHN Team (Women) 2016 (3.
5) 1/2-1/2} 14. Qb2 Nd7 15. Bb5 $1 f6 16. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4] With a clear
advantage for White.}) 13. O-O (13. dxe6 $5) 13... Nc5 14. Rfe1 Bb7 15. Rad1
exd5 16. Bxd5 (16. exd5 {Later on, White could try to install a piece on c6.})
16... Bxd5 17. exd5 $14 {[%csl Yd5] Despite Black having a bit more breathing
room for his pieces, the passed pawn is still annoying and he had a difficult
task trying to hold it in Borovikov,V (2582)-Wirig,A (2464) Pfalz op 2nd 2009 
(4) 1-0} *

