1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 $5 {As the name suggests, the Chigorin Defense was
introduced at the high level by the great Mikhail Ivanovich Chigorin more than
120 years ago. Nevertheless, this original opening first appears in historical
registers back in 1837(!). This opening illustrates very well Chigorin's bold
approach to the game. Instead of safely protect the pawn, Black goes for quick
development and immediately puts pressure on White's center. Of course, as we
are going to witness, such a brave opening concept has some drawbacks.} 3. Nf3
{This is the main move which is enough to give White a pleasant position.} (3.
Nc3 {is Avrukh's recommendation which also seems to be sound.}) 3... Bg4 {
The logical continuation of Black's plan.} (3... e6 {wouldn't make sense since
Black wants to use his pieces to put pressure on White's centre.}) 4. cxd5 {
The classical continuation, forcing Black to give the bishop pair away.} Bxf3
5. gxf3 $1 {Initiating the complicated Chigorin's strategic battle.} (5. dxc6 {
fails to create problems. For example:} Bxc6 6. Nc3 e6 7. e4 Bb4 8. f3 f5 $1 {
Black has obtained a very active position.}) 5... Qxd5 6. e3 e5 (6... e6 {and})
(6... O-O-O {are more solid ways to play. Nevertheless, these continuations
are not following Black's opening concept. White generally obtains a slightly
better position by simple means.} 7. Nc3 Qh5 8. f4 $1 {The exchange of the
queens allows White to eliminate Black's dynamic possibilities. The arising
endgames are favorable for White because of the bishop pair and the strong
control of the center.} Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 e6 10. Bd2 (10. Bg2 Nce7 11. Ke2 Nf5 12.
Bd2 Nf6 13. Rhg1 $5 h6 14. Rac1 Kb8 15. Ne4 $1 {One idea for Black is to put
the knights in good positions, taking advantage of White's slightly damaged
structure. That is why it looks good to exchange one of the knights.} Nxe4 16.
Bxe4 g6 17. Ba5 Rd7 {and here} 18. d5 $1 {gave White an advantage.} exd5 19.
Bxf5 gxf5 20. Bc3 $1 f6 $8 21. Bxf6 Rhh7 22. Rg8 Rhf7 23. Bg7 $1 Rd8 24. Bxh6
$16 {Rodshtein,M (2494)-Martinovic,S (2367) Budapest FS08 GM 2006 (3) 1-0})
10... Nf6 (10... Nce7 11. Rc1 c6 12. b4 $1 {A natural idea - White should open
the position for his bishops.} Nf6 $2 13. b5 h6 14. Bg2 $16 {[%csl Gc6][%cal
Yc1c8] ; Miladinovic,I (2598)-Rapport,J (2115) Belgrade Trophy 19th 2006 (3)
1-0}) 11. Bg2 Ne7 12. Ke2 Kb8 13. Na4 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ga4c5] This move prepares
not just Nc5, but also White's queenside expansion with b2-b4.} Nf5 {In this
position, it took me some time to understand White's next move} 14. Rhg1 $1 ({
The importance of White's last move becomes obvious when looking at a recent
Ding Liren's game} 14. Rhd1 Nd5 15. b4 $5 h6 $1 {[%cal Yg7g5] Black's
counterplay in these positions is based on the advance g7-g5.} 16. Nc5 g5 17.
fxg5 hxg5 18. h3 Be7 19. a4 Nh4 20. Bf1 {Ding Liren (2772)-Stevic,H (2616)
33rd ECC Open 2017 2017 (4.7) 1-0 Although Ding has won the game; it is clear
that his opening was not a success, and Black could even have taken the
initiative with} e5 $5 21. dxe5 a5 $1 $13) 14... Nd5 (14... h6 {is not a real
threat now. For example:} 15. Nc5 c6 16. Nd3 $1 g5 $2 17. Ne5 Nd6 18. Bb4 $36)
15. Rac1 {In such positions, White has an instructive plan that should be
remembered: transferring the knight to d3 via c5, then making Ne5 a move that
should always be counted. From d3, the knight also supports the pawn expansion
on the queenside. Another point is that White is always playing with a
comfortable space advantage. Meanwhile, Black has no clear way to generate
counterplay, thus making White's position easier. One illustrative variation
could be} g6 16. Nc5 Bd6 17. b4 h6 18. a4 $14 {and if Black insists on the
plan with} g5 $2 19. Bxd5 $1 exd5 20. fxg5 Bxh2 (20... hxg5 21. Rxg5 Ne7 22.
Rg7 f5 {Black manages to regain the pawn, but his position is still worse} 23.
b5 Rxh2 24. Bb4 $1 {[%cal Yc5d3,Yc5a6] with threats like Nd3 and Na6!?+.
White's activity gives him a clear advantage.}) 21. Rg2 Bd6 (21... hxg5 22.
Rxg5) 22. gxh6 Rxh6 23. Rg5 Ne7 24. b5 $14 {Black remains under unpleasant
pressure. White's next step is Bb4 followed by Nd3, forcing the exchange of
the dark-squared bishop. The d6-bishop is a very important piece which
protects many important squares in Black's camp.}) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9.
bxc3 {[%csl Gd2,Gf1] This is the one of the main tabyias in Chigorin Defense.
At first sight, one could get very impressed by White's strong centre and the
bishop pair, but things are not so simple: The piece pressure considerably
restricts the pawn advances, and the knights can be very useful for blockading
purposes. The c4-square could be an excellent outpost, and if White eventually
advances the pawns with c3-c4 followed by d4-d5, then c5 becomes another one.
Due to the doubled pawns on the kingside, Black is probably going to have some
solid square there. On the other hand, besides his compact central pawns,
White can make use of the semi-open "b" and "g." files.} Qd6 $1 {Anticipating
ideas like c3-c4 and d4-d5.} (9... exd4 {is the second most played move, but I
don't like it. Black releases the tension in the centre, and White can develop
very easily.} 10. cxd4 Nge7 {Some years ago, I faced this position and played}
11. Rg1 O-O (11... O-O-O $5 {looks more principled, leaving the g7-pawn to its
fate. Black intends to play Nf5 followed by Rhe8.} 12. f4 $1 {[%cal Yf1g2]}
Rhe8 13. Bg2 Qe6 14. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 15. axb3 $14 {White enjoys an obvious
advantage in the endgame.}) 12. Bc3 $5 {When checking in the database, I have
seen that the last time that this move was played was in my game, back in
2013! Nevertheless, I still think that this is the most logical way to exploit
the disadvantages of 9...exd4. Also, White is planning to create threats
against Black's king using e3-e4 followed by d4-d5.} (12. f4 {[%cal Yf1g2,
Yd1b3] looks like another good option}) 12... Ng6 $6 (12... Rad8 {was what I
had in mind} 13. e4 Qh5 14. d5 Ng6 (14... Ne5 15. f4 $1 Nf3+ 16. Qxf3 $3 Qxf3
17. Rxg7+ Kh8 18. Rg3+ Qxc3+ 19. Rxc3 $16) 15. f4 $1 Qxh2 16. Qg4 $36 {White's
initiative looks promising. This position was played once and the game
followed with} Rfe8 $1 17. O-O-O $5 Qxf2 {Bercys, S (2360)-Finegold,B (2563)
Chicago op 15th 2006 (3) 0-1} 18. Rg2 Qe3+ 19. Kb2 $13) (12... f5 $2 {prevents
e3-e4, but after} 13. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 14. axb3 {[%cal Yd4d5] Black's position
seems to be very difficult. For example:} Nd5 15. Bc4 Rad8 16. e4 fxe4 17. fxe4
Rfe8 18. f3 Kf8 19. Bb2 Ne3 20. d5 $1 Ne5 21. Bxe5 Rxe5 22. Rxa7 $16) 13. Bd3 {
[%cal Yd3e4,Ya1b1] White is already better.} Rfe8 14. Be4 {Black tried to
complicate matters with} Rxe4 $6 (14... Qh5 15. Rb1 Qxh2 16. Kf1 Rab8 17. d5
Nce7 18. Qd4 $36 {[%csl Ga7,Gg7]}) 15. fxe4 Qxe4 {but after} 16. Qb1 $1 {
White is technically winning - Quintiliano Pinto,R (2315)-Ribeiro,A (1843)
Vitoria Cup 2013 (1) 1-0}) (9... Qd7 $5 {was recently tried by Rapport} 10. Rb1
{This is the better way to attack the b7-pawn.} (10. Qb3 Nge7 11. Qxb7 O-O {
[%csl Yb7] This is a better version for Black since the queen is a little bit
misplaced on b7 and should waste some time to get back into the game.} 12. Qb1
Rfe8 $44 {Carron, J (2394)-Miralles,G (2469) SUI-chT Switzerland 2010 (7.4) 0-1
}) 10... O-O-O $5 ({In a case of} 10... b6 {, White can play} 11. f4 {As we
have already seen, this is a thematic idea.} exf4 12. e4 $1 {In this way,
White gets rid of his double pawns and keeps a strong centre.} Nge7 {Hartge,G 
(2140)-Xu,X (2401) TCh-GER Junior U20 2017 2017 (4.1) 0-1} 13. Bxf4 O-O 14. Bg2
{[%cal Ye1g1] After completing the development, White will maintain a stable
