1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5 $6 {The Baltic Defense is a sideline variation that it is
not so frequent in high level games. Nevertheless, White could get caught by
surprise if he is not familiar with the theory. That is why it is important to
know how to answer this strange approach.} 3. cxd5 $1 {Although this is not
the only path to an advantage, I like this practical and easy to play move.} ({
For example,} 3. Nc3 e6 4. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5] generally is the best way to
exploit the bishop's absence on the queenside, but now} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Yc6b4,
Yc6d4] leads to some complications. This is what our opponent will be aiming
for in this line.}) 3... Bxb1 $6 {White already gets a comfortable advantage
after this move.} ({If Black tries to regain the pawn without giving away the
bishop pair with} 3... Nf6 $6 {then the simple} 4. Nc3 {is better for White}
Nxd5 (4... c6 $2 {is not really a good sacrifice} 5. dxc6 Nxc6 {Yermolinsky,A 
(2580)-Chernoff,J US op 096th Concord 1995 (4) 1-0} 6. d5 $1 {is actually
winning for White} Na5 7. e4 $1 $18) 5. Qb3 $1 Nxc3 (5... e6 6. e4 Nxc3 7. exf5
$16) 6. bxc3 b6 {and even with simple developing moves White has a better
position} 7. Nf3 e6 8. Nd2 {[%cal Ye2e4]} Be7 9. g3 $1 $14 {[%cal Yf1g2]}) ({
Of course} 3... Qxd5 $2 4. Nc3 Qa5 5. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Ye2e4] is very bad for
Black}) 4. Qa4+ $1 {A nice intermediate check.} (4. Rxb1 Qxd5 {[%csl Ya2]
attacks the a2-pawn}) 4... c6 $8 (4... Qd7 5. Qxd7+ Nxd7 6. Rxb1 Ngf6 7. Nf3 (
7. f3 Nxd5 8. e4 $2 {would be bad because of} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Yb4a2,Gb4c2,Gc2d4]}
) 7... Nb6 8. e3 Nbxd5 9. a3 e6 10. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Ye3e4] and since Black's
knights doesn't have good squares, White is much better.}) 5. Rxb1 (5. dxc6 {
looks also good} Nxc6 6. Rxb1 e5 $1 {[%cal Yf8b4] a move that should score
very well in blitz games} (6... Qxd4 7. Qxd4 Nxd4 8. e3 Nc6 9. b4 $1) 7. Bd2 $1
(7. dxe5 $4 Bb4+ $19) 7... Qxd4 8. Qxd4 exd4 9. g3 $14 {In this open position,
White's bishop pair secures a stable edge.}) 5... Qxd5 6. Nf3 {White's
position is already better because of the bishop pair and the pawn majority in
the center.} Nd7 (6... Nf6 7. e3 Nbd7 {Black threatens to play 8...Nb6, thus
winning the a2-pawn. White solves this problem by playing} 8. b4 $1 {[%cal
Yb4b5] getting ready to open the queenside} e5 $6 {This active approach is
rather dubious because Black opens the position for White's bishops.} 9. dxe5
Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. b5 $36 {Sadler,M (2575)-Condie,M (2450) BCF-ch 82nd
Swansea 1995 (3) 1-0}) 7. b4 $1 Ngf6 8. e3 e6 9. Qc2 {[%cal Yf1c4,Yf1d3,Ge3e4]
Preparing Bc4 or Bd3 followed by e3-e4.} Bd6 (9... Be7 {is too passive} 10. Bd3
O-O (10... a5 11. e4 Qh5 12. e5 $1 Nd5 13. bxa5 Nb4 14. Qd2 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 Rxa5
16. Rxb7 $16 {Grandelius,N (2476)-Lejlic,S (2362) Sarajevo Bosna op 40th 2010 
(4) 1-0} Rxa2 $2 17. Qc4 $18) 11. O-O e5 (11... Rfd8 12. e4 Qh5 {Shulman,Y 
(2548)-Mezentsev,V (2376) Koltanowski Memorial op 2000 (5) 1-0} 13. Bf4 $16 {
[%csl Ye5] stopping e6-e5. Black's position is very annoying.}) 12. e4 Qd6 13.
Bb2 exd4 14. Bxd4 {[%cal Ye4e5]} Ng4 {White got a nice position with} 15. e5 $5
Ndxe5 16. Bxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Rfe1 Qg5 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Rb3 $1 $40 {
Chigladze,I (2375)-Grigoriev,A (2281) Antakya op 2010 (5) 1-0 with strong
