1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 $5 {This exotic position is called Symmetrical or Austrian
Defense. Probably, this is Black's most aggressive response to 2.c4. Although
this line seems a bit dubious, some strong grandmasters like Wang Hao and
Mamedyarov have played it recently. If White is not very precise, Black has a
good chance of solving his opening problems.} 3. cxd5 {The most principled
move. White wants to force the black queen to come in the center.} (3. dxc5 d4
$5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. e3 e5 6. exd4 exd4 7. Bd3 Bxc5 {looks interesting but the
game is far from being one-sided.}) (3. Nf3 {and}) (3. e3 {just transpose to
another variation. After these moves, White does not try to take advantage of
Black's move order.}) 3... Qxd5 ({Against,} 3... Nf6 {White has an interesting
idea:} 4. e4 $5 Nxe4 5. dxc5 Nxc5 6. Nc3 {Black has problems to continue the
development} ({Another option is} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Nc3 exd5 8. Qxd5 $1 Be7 9. Qxd8+
Bxd8 10. Be3 $1 {even after the queen's exchange, White keeps a notable lead
in the development.} Nba6 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O-O $1 Ndc5 14.
Bxc5 $1 Nxc5 15. Rhe1+ {Even after multiple exchanges, Black's problems
persist, and his position remains unpleasant.} Ne6 16. Nd4 $1 {Instructive
transformation of a dynamic advantage into a static one - White allows Black
to finish the development at the price of having a weak pawn on e6.} O-O 17.
Nxe6 fxe6 18. f3 Bc7 19. h3 $14 {[%csl Ge6] ;Gleizerov,E (2581)-Berkell,P 
(2310) Rilton Cup 32nd 2002 (3) 1-0 and White showed good technique in}) 6...
e5 $5 {This move doesn't change the nature of the position. White's d5-pawn is
very annoying while Black still has problems to complete the development.} 7.
Nf3 Bd6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Be3 Nbd7 11. Nb5 $1 Nf6 12. Rc1 b6 13. b4 $1
Nb7 14. Qb3 $14 {Berkvens,J (2455)-Zaitsev,M (2455) BL2-West 0304 2003 [1] 1-0}
) 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 $1 {If Black manages to complete the development without
compromising his position, his opening concept would be a success. To avoid
such a scenario, White should play very energetically.} Qa5 {Not the safest
square to place the queen, but other options were inferior.} ({For example} 
5... Qd8 $6 {is well met by} 6. Qxd4 $1 {This move already puts Black under
pressure.} Bd7 {Here, White obtains a pleasant position with the simple} (6...
Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 (7... a6 8. Nd5 $18) 8. Ndb5 $1 Na6 {[%csl Yb5] The b5-knight
is perfectly placed to keep the Na6 tied to the defense of c7. Additionally,
the a7-pawn is under pressure. White can follow with} 9. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] In
such kind of positions, the pressure along the long diagonal could be very
annoying. The following sequence is quite typical for this line.} Bd7 10. Bg2
Bc6 11. O-O e6 12. a3 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Be7 14. Be3 b6 15. b4 O-O 16. Rac1 {
[%csl Ya6,Ga7] Black has the a6-knight out of play, and the Ra8 is tied to the
miserable job of protecting the a7-pawn.}) (6... Nc6 $6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 (7...
Nxd8 8. Nb5 Ne6 9. Ng5 $1 Nxg5 10. Bxg5 Kd8 {Vera Pons,F (2162)-Zlygostev,A
Internet Section 08A g/8'+2" blitz 2004 (1) 1-0} 11. Rd1+ Bd7 12. Nd6 $1 {
White is winning} f6 (12... Nh6 13. Nxb7+) 13. Nf7+ Ke8 14. Nxh8 fxg5 15. Nf7
$1 $18) 8. Bf4 {[%csl Gd8] White has kept his better development. The
vulnerable black king makes White's advantage even bigger.} f6 9. O-O-O+ Bd7 {
Karsa,L (2340)-Groszpeter,A (2480) HUN-ch36 Budapest 1980 1/2-1/2} 10. e4 e5
11. Be3 Ke8 12. Bc4 $16 {and Black's position remains difficult.}) 7. Ne5 Nf6
8. Nxd7 Nbxd7 9. g3 {[%csl Yc1,Yf1][%cal Gf1g2] with an obvious advantage due
to the bishop pair. This is the dream position for every Catalan player -
Dittmar,P (2344)-Lucchi,L (2112) Cesenatico op 17th 2013 (9) 1-0}) (5... Qd6 6.
Qxd4 e6 {also gave advantage for White after} 7. Bf4 $1 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 9. g3
Bb4 10. Bg2 Ne7 11. O-O Nd7 12. Ne4 $16 {Ivanisevic,I (2645)-Miladinovic,I 
(2555) SRB-ch Vrnjacka Banja 2012 (3) 1-0}) 6. Nxd4 {This should be the tabiya
of this opening: The big question is whether White can transform his lead in
the development in some stable advantage.} Nf6 ({Mamedyarov has also played} 
6... e5 $6 {but the analysis suggests that this move is quite risky} 7. Nb3 (7.
Ndb5 $5 {deserves attention since White's score is surprisingly high with this
move.}) 7... Qc7 (7... Qd8 $2 {The exchange of the queens does not help Black.}
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. g3 $1 {the effect is exactly the opposite: the king which
stuck in the center makes his development harder.} Bb4 10. Bg2 Ne7 11. O-O Bxc3
$6 12. bxc3 Nbc6 13. Rd1+ Kc7 14. Ba3 $16 {Bartel,M (2629)-Krol,P (1666)
POL-ch Rapid rapid 2017 (1) 1-0}) 8. Nb5 $5 Qc6 (8... Qe7 9. Bg5 $1 Nf6 10. Qc2
Nc6 11. O-O-O $1 {[%cal Yb5d6]}) 9. e3 Qd7 (9... a6 10. Na5 $1 Qd7 (10... Qb6
11. Nc4 $1 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 Qc7 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Gd6]}) (10... Qc5
11. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Ya1c1]}) 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Re5]} axb5 13.
Nb6+ Kc6 14. Nxa8 b6 {[%csl Ra8] the knight seems trapped, but White can bring
it back into play with} 15. Bd2 {[%cal Ya1c1]} Kb7 16. Rc1 Nc6 17. Bxb5 Bd7 18.
O-O Nge7 {Okay, it was not possible to bring the knight back, but after} 19.
Nxb6 $1 Kxb6 20. a4 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ya4a5] White has two dangerous passed pawns
supported by the bishop pair} Nd5 21. Rfd1 $18) 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {Goganov,A 
