1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 $5 {The Albin Counter Gambit is an old line that remains
popular even nowadays. With the help of the modern computers, such a dynamic
openings are very playable. That is why we can face the Albin at every level.}
3. dxe5 d4 {[%csl Yd4] Black sacrificed a pawn in order to gain space in the
center, thus making difficult for White to comfortably develop his pieces. At
the same time, Black intends to regain the pawn by means of Nc6 followed by
the maneuver Ng8-e7-g6.} 4. Nf3 ({When I was a naive child, one of the first
traps that I fell into was this one:} 4. e3 $2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 dxe3 $1 {and I had
to accept an inferior position after} 6. fxe3 ({Unfortunately,} 6. Bxb4 {
loses to} exf2+ 7. Ke2 fxg1=N+ $1 $19 {I was shocked and amazed at the same
time by the beauty of chess.}) 6... Qh4+ 7. g3 Qe4) 4... Nc6 (4... c5 $2 {
now allows} 5. e3 $1 {since the check on b4 is not available}) {Now the simple}
5. a3 $1 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gb2b4] is a very reliable option, preventing Bb4+
and preparing b2-b4 at the same time.} Nge7 {This is the most popular move
nowadays.} ({Another important move is} 5... Bg4 {Black is going for quick
development. Although 6.Nbd2 is a solid option, the move} 6. h3 $5 {has drawn
my attention because it was played just in a few games.The idea of getting the
bishop pair looks interesting.} Bxf3 (6... Bh5 $2 {allows White to develop and
consolidate his advantage with} 7. g4 $1 Bg6 8. b4 Qe7 9. Bf4 $16) 7. exf3 Nxe5
8. f4 Nc6 {Also, in this position the best move was not played yet:} (8... Ng6
{was played twice. Black wants to protect the pawn by c7-c5, but the knight is
misplaced on g6.} 9. g3 $5 $146 {the real idea of this move is to restrict the
g6-knight and prepare some unpleasant h4-h5 ideas.} Nf6 (9... Qe7+ $6 {doesn't
really disturb White's development.} 10. Be2 O-O-O 11. O-O Nf6 12. Re1 Qd7 13.
Bf1 {Maybe, it seems strange to claim a clear advantage for White already, but
this is because Black has no clear plan to proceed - the passed pawn is
harmless, there are no attacking chances on the kingside, and he has at least
two problems to worry about: after an eventual b2-b4 by White, both the king
and the d4-pawn will be in danger. An illustrative line would be} h5 14. b4 h4
15. g4 d3 $2 16. Ra2 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Yf4f5,Ga2d2]}) 10. h4 $1 h5 (10...
Qe7+ 11. Be2 O-O-O 12. O-O {[%cal Rh4h5]} h5 13. Bd3 Qd7 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal
Yb2b4]}) 11. Bd3 $1 {From this position, the bishop exerts an annoying
pressure against White's kingside. At the same time, White leaves the
g2-square available for his king.} (11. Bg2 {is also good and natural}) 11...
Be7 ({In a case of} 11... Qe7+ 12. Kf1 O-O-O 13. Nd2 Kb8 14. Kg2 Qd7 15. b4 Ng4
